Fukushima and the collapse of derivatives
CAMBRIDGE – Financial commentators have compared the Japanese earthquake, tsunami, and nuclear disaster to the role of derivatives in the 2008 financial crisis.
The similarity is quite clear: each of these activities generates substantial profits and involves a very low but potentially explosive risk.
Nevertheless, the similarity between the two types of crisis ends where the way to prevent their recurrence begins.
In the case of the Fukushima nuclear power plant, a once-in-a-century flood, combined with usually harmless design flaws, caused the shutdown of the cooling water circulation in the reactors and significant radiation leaks.
With regard to financial markets, an unanticipated collapse in real estate values, combined with design flaws in derivative and repo markets, has damaged the ability of major financial institutions to meet their debt obligations.
Although the underlying risks originate outside the systems—a tsunami for Fukushima, excessive investment in mortgage loans for financial institutions—design flaws and bad luck have caused the systems to be unable to contain the damage.
In the United States, AIG, Bear Stearns, and Lehman Brothers—all with significant investments in derivatives and/or real estate—collapsed, causing a credit freeze in the markets for several long weeks.
We now understand quite well the risks and design flaws of Fukushima.
One cannot say the same about the risks of derivatives, which have shaken the global economy.
In Fukushima, teams of workers are bravely trying to stop the radiation leaks.
On the contrary, for derivative products, similar efforts are misdirected and will not allow us to avoid the next financial crisis.
We are recreating derivative products and similar financial structures, repeating the same errors that are still active.
Financial actors use financial products to transfer risk: for example, one actor accepts the risk of euro fluctuations but does not want the risk related to the yen, whereas for another, it will be the opposite.
In this case, the first promises to provide euros by June 1st, and the second promises to provide yen.
If one currency loses value relative to the other, the loser pays the difference.
The rests are financial transactions.
Financial firms sell assets, such as Treasury securities or mortgage-backed debt, for cash and promise to repurchase these assets later, typically the following day (hence the name "repo," which is an abbreviation of the English verb "repurchase" – or repurchase, note by the translator).
The problem is that the cash generated from these short-term repos constitutes a large part of the balance sheets of the most important financial institutions, which implies that even minor financial tremors can strongly affect them.
Some institutions may then find themselves deprived of repo financing, as in 2008, and subsequently fail, like Bear Stearns.
Taken individually, transactions involving derivatives or repos are scarcely blameworthy.
Each one separately legitimately transfers the risk to those who are better able to bear it, or allows for financial participation.
However, when they are overused by institutions that are vital at the systemic level, they can cause the financial system to collapse due to its design flaws.
Even today, approximately 70% of the liabilities of major U.S. financial institutions consist of very short-term loans, such as overnight repos.
In the United States, the main design flaws are found in bankruptcy legislation, which exempts derivatives and repurchase agreements from most usual bankruptcy constraints.
For example, investors who hold derivative contracts or loans with financially weakened institutions may seize the company's assets before—and at the expense of—its regular creditors. In doing so, they can determine the company's fate, even though, with a little more time, the company might have survived.
Such actions ruined AIG, Bear Stearns, and others during the financial crisis.
Worse still, because investors in derivatives and repo markets find themselves at the front of the line for repayments in so many ways, they have less incentive to encourage market discipline by closely examining the solvency of their counterparties and carefully rationing their exposure to any single counterparty.
Typically, they will be refunded anyway.
Certainly, someone must be first.
Other financial actors must bear more risk because the exemptions for derivatives and repo market participants place them at the forefront in the event of bankruptcy.
Normally, one would expect others to have an interest in encouraging more market discipline.
But the actor that follows in this line is often the American government, as the guarantor of "too-big-to-fail" financial institutions (too important to let fail, translator's note). However, the government is poorly positioned to regulate these markets on a day-to-day basis.
He is not financially agile; he often sticks to the regulated market; and, when economic conditions are good, no official would want to spoil the party.
The American Congress had an opportunity to address this flaw in the major overhaul of finance that it adopted last summer through the Dodd-Frank bill.
But he did not grasp it.
If investors in derivatives, repos, and credit-default swaps (credit event derivatives, translator's note) did not receive preferential treatment, they would behave differently.
First and foremost, they would more often insist that their counterparts be adequately capitalized.
They accepted the risk generated by extremely low capitalizations when it essentially involved American government money; they would be less inclined to do so if it were their own money at stake.
The public perceives Fukushima-type risks and derivative product risks differently.
Many people fear nuclear risks, which are alarming and are causing a slowdown in the industry that must deal with security concerns.
But the markets for derivatives and repos present risks that are poorly understood, difficult to communicate through the media, and complicated for politicians to debate and resolve.
During a crisis, these markets attract public attention and scorn, but when the economy stabilizes again, ordinary people lose all interest, leaving the financial sector to control its own destiny with the legislative body.
Regarding Fukushima-type risks, analysts are already discussing how nuclear power plants can be designed and constructed to contain risks related to earthquakes and tsunamis through passive cooling systems.
Today, it is considered possible to design nuclear power plants capable of keeping the fuel rods cool even in the event of a complete loss of electrical power.
On the other hand, little significant progress has been made so far to prevent the damages that the priority of derivatives and secured claims in the event of bankruptcy could cause during a new financial system crisis.
New rules are being developed that require end users (such as oil companies using derivatives to protect against unanticipated changes in oil prices) and others to post high-quality collateral.
However, these rules do not address the main problem: the weak market discipline incentives for major financial institutions.
It is as if we are responding to Fukushima by better controlling gas emissions in oil extraction projects.
We should examine how to have derivative and repo investors fully bear the risk associated with their decisions when they conduct transactions with financially vital, systemically important institutions.
Instead, we survived the 2008 financial tsunami only to rebuild in the same place, with the same financial flaws and according to the same faulty design.
